---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section
  id="sessions"
  class="border-y border-neutral-900 bg-neutral-900/40 px-6 py-20 md:py-28"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
      >
        Sessions become shared memory
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        The other half is memory. Instead of dissolving, every session is
        captured and <mark>connected to the repositories and PRs it
        touched</mark>, so the reasoning behind a code change stays attached to
        the change itself.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="lg:order-last">
        <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
          <p>
            Sessions also connect to each other, because work builds on other
            work. The fix you ship today leans on a refactor from last month
            and a decision someone made in spring. Captured sessions form a
            graph that mirrors that reality.
          </p>
          <p>
            So when a bug lands on a feature you touched in a session weeks
            ago, or that a teammate touched, the agent finds that session,
            references it, and pulls its knowledge into the current one. You
            are effectively <mark>picking the brain of the developer who
            left</mark>: what was decided, what was ruled out, why it looks the
            way it does.
          </p>
          <p class="font-medium text-neutral-100">
            The reasoning stops walking out the door, because it never lived
            behind one door to begin with.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <VizPlaceholder
          label="SessionNetwork island: sessions linking to repos, PRs, and each other into a growing graph"
          ratio="aspect-[4/3]"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
